ODE XII.

‘ What man wilt thou sing of, Clio? what demigod? what god ἶ)- sing of, till the hill of Helicon rings his name again, or the woods of Haemus follow to listen, as they did when Orpheus sang? What god, but Jove first, and Pallas next, Liber, Diana, Phoebus. For demigods, Hercules and the Twin Brethren who calm the stormy sea. And of men : Romulus and all the Roman worthies3 Marcellus, the lustre of whose name grows with each generation ; the Julian house, which outshines all others as the moon outshines the stars ; Augustus, the hope of the human race, the vicegerent of Jove himself)

The framework of the Ode is suggested by the opening of Pind. Ol. 2 · ἀναξιφόρμιγγες ὕμνοι τίνα θεόν, τίν’ ἥρωα, τίνα δ’ ἄνδρα κελαδήσομεν;

But after the question has been asked the resemblance eeases. In Pindar it is answered immediately: ‘The god is Zeus, the hero Hercules, the man Theron,’ and all three are directly connected with the Olympian
